WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:22.560
This is Cthulhu. It's a film that came out in 2008. Not many people appear to have seen

00:22.560 --> 00:24.880
it.

00:24.880 --> 00:29.560
As a teenager, I was obsessed with the works of Howard Phillips Lovecraft. Lovecraft was

00:29.560 --> 00:35.120
a pioneer in Pulp Horror Fiction, immediately gripping with his cavalcade of creative monsters,

00:35.120 --> 00:41.020
epic scope, terrible fates, and a unique philosophy about the terror of the existence of gods

00:41.020 --> 00:45.400
greater than the human consciousness could allow. The man's work was inspirational

00:45.400 --> 00:50.920
and moving to me. It made me think, made me dream, made me want to be a writer. Also,

00:50.920 --> 00:57.160
seeing cool new words like Theosophists, or Non-Euclidean, or sentences like The Blood

00:57.160 --> 01:04.760
Roots grew insolent in their chromatic perversion made me feel smart. I liked thinking I was

01:04.760 --> 01:05.760
smart.

01:05.760 --> 01:08.640
I was a big fan of the role-playing game, too. I just really liked the way that it dealt

01:08.640 --> 01:12.880
with the mythos and how you interact with it, and the way it modeled sanity was really

01:12.880 --> 01:19.200
good, too. And, hang on, can we, can someone find out who did this and why? I've been confused

01:19.200 --> 01:20.840
by this for like a decade now.

01:20.840 --> 01:26.520
As my interest grew and I ran out of stories by, inspired by, or about Lovecraft to read,

01:26.520 --> 01:31.320
I started playing or watching any game or film even remotely based on his work. I'd

01:31.320 --> 01:35.880
seen Re-Animator and its sequels, and From Beyond, and I was even about to watch Hellraiser

01:35.880 --> 01:39.600
when I found an interview with Clive Barker where he said he didn't like Lovecraft's

01:39.600 --> 01:44.160
writing very much and decided not to watch the film out of some misguided sense of spite.

01:44.160 --> 01:49.160
That was how I did things back then, apparently.

01:49.160 --> 01:52.840
I'd heard that Guillermo del Toro was going to adapt At the Mountains of Madness, one

01:52.840 --> 01:56.560
of the best of Lovecraft's stories, and I couldn't wait for that. It turned out

01:56.560 --> 01:59.920
I shouldn't have waited because it didn't happen. It was in development hell for a very

01:59.920 --> 02:01.560
long time, and then it was never greenlit.

02:01.560 --> 02:06.440
Then, as I was scraping the bottom of the barrel and watching fan films on YouTube,

02:06.440 --> 02:11.880
I eventually found out about Cthulhu. It was named after Lovecraft's most famous creation,

02:11.880 --> 02:15.680
and it had been made so recently that it might have been able to take advantage of the kinds

02:15.680 --> 02:20.960
of effects and production techniques possible in modern filmmaking that something of truly

02:20.960 --> 02:27.520
epic scale might actually have been possible. Cthulhu is not that film. Cthulhu isn't in

02:27.520 --> 02:31.800
the film. It isn't even based on the short story The Call of Cthulhu. It's actually

02:31.800 --> 02:37.000
a loose, very loose, interpretation of The Shadow Over Innsmouth. In that story, the

02:37.000 --> 02:41.320
narrator investigates a New England fishing town where the people are strange and unwelcoming

02:41.320 --> 02:45.840
to outsiders. He eventually discovers that the people of the town worship a godlike fish

02:45.840 --> 02:51.320
creature named Dagon and its monstrous children, and have begun breeding with those creatures,

02:51.320 --> 02:55.580
and their descendants eventually transform into monsters themselves to take to the water

02:55.580 --> 03:00.800
and live forever beneath the sea with Dagon. After barely escaping with his life, the narrator

03:00.800 --> 03:06.280
realizes that his family tree comes from Innsmouth, and he is slowly becoming one of them, too,

03:06.280 --> 03:11.680
and he's starting to like it and relish the chance to worship Dagon for all time. It's

03:11.680 --> 03:16.280
a really good story, and it's an excellent example of early 20th century American horror,

03:16.280 --> 03:20.800
with the narrator's final change serving as a genuinely uncomfortable and fascinating

03:20.800 --> 03:26.960
twist. It's really a true classic. This film is about a gay college professor called Russell,

03:26.960 --> 03:30.800
who learns that his mother has passed away and returns to his hometown for her funeral.

03:30.800 --> 03:35.440
Russell's father is the leader of a strange religious cult, and also deeply homophobic,

03:35.440 --> 03:39.760
along with many of the rest of the townspeople. Russell realizes the cult has designs on him

03:39.760 --> 03:44.120
of some kind, and something strange is going on. He reconnects with an old lover from his

03:44.120 --> 03:49.000
past and tries to learn the truth as the people become increasingly hostile towards his search.

03:49.000 --> 03:54.440
In lieu of looking at the tangible specifics of the horror, the beliefs of the cult, or

03:54.440 --> 03:59.400
portraying the monsters from the original story, the film focuses on Russell's own

03:59.400 --> 04:05.000
emotional state, his experiences and dreams, and relation to the people he encounters as

04:05.000 --> 04:09.760
he tries to understand what is happening. When monsters do briefly appear, there's

04:09.760 --> 04:14.960
not really much to see. The story isn't really concerned with them.

04:14.960 --> 04:20.160
When I first saw this film, I decided that I hated it more than any other film. It had

04:20.160 --> 04:25.280
taken something I cared about and enjoyed, and removed the things I thought made it interesting

04:25.280 --> 04:30.160
and valuable. It made an existential horror about god-like creatures that care not for

04:30.160 --> 04:35.120
human affairs into a story where the god in question never turns up or does anything

04:35.120 --> 04:41.360
or is even really talked about in it. And even the name's technically the wrong name

04:41.360 --> 04:46.800
of the god. Oh, and if you put the disc in a PC, the label doesn't even spell Cthulhu

04:46.800 --> 04:53.960
properly! It's such an easy word to spell! The whole film felt like a betrayal. The camera

04:53.960 --> 04:59.760
sometimes sits very still, trapping you with Russell in situations neither of you want

04:59.760 --> 05:03.960
to be in, for conversations he doesn't want to be having with people he doesn't want to

05:03.960 --> 05:04.960
see.

05:04.960 --> 05:07.960
So, um, how's the, uh, how's the church?

05:07.960 --> 05:10.960
How's the gay life treating you, Russell?

05:10.960 --> 05:16.560
It's my life.

05:16.560 --> 05:17.560
Is it satisfying?

05:17.560 --> 05:18.560
Are you fulfilled?

05:18.560 --> 05:21.960
What do you want to know? You want to know what we do?

05:21.960 --> 05:23.960
Danny, please, just stay, stay out of this.

05:24.160 --> 05:30.960
I didn't want any of this. I wanted something big, something epic, something focusing on

05:30.960 --> 05:35.560
the horror of the big monsters, the sheer scope of the cosmos beyond our reach and the

05:35.560 --> 05:40.200
nihilistic implications of being unimportant in the face of seemingly all-powerful things

05:40.200 --> 05:44.680
that can decide our fate on a whim. For so much of it, it was such an uncomfortable and

05:44.680 --> 05:50.520
personal and low-key horror. A human horror I wasn't really prepared for and was sure

05:50.520 --> 05:51.520
I didn't want.

05:54.760 --> 06:01.680
But as I got older and lived a decade of new experiences, to put it simply, I grew up.

06:01.680 --> 06:05.480
I just sort of realized one day that I was capable of being romantically attracted to

06:05.480 --> 06:10.680
men as well as women. I realized I was different from how I'd even thought of myself. I'd

06:10.680 --> 06:15.680
just sort of naturally seen myself as straight, and even if I didn't think I thought of it

06:15.680 --> 06:21.640
this way, on some primal level, I'd thought of being straight as being normal. I didn't

06:21.640 --> 06:25.400
know why I thought like that. It's probably a mix of not really thinking too hard about

06:25.400 --> 06:30.160
these things at the time combined with the vague notions and expectations our society

06:30.160 --> 06:34.440
tends to have towards people's sexuality. But one day I looked in the mirror and saw

06:34.440 --> 06:42.600
myself as not who I thought I was. I saw myself as an outsider from me, from the identity

06:42.600 --> 06:47.920
I'd assumed for myself. And then I had a few difficult conversations with troublesome

06:47.920 --> 06:52.620
people about those feelings. I'd always experienced termophobia. I was an effeminate

06:52.620 --> 06:57.200
boy growing up, but I hadn't really cared because at the time I'd not really accepted

06:57.200 --> 07:01.680
it as an insult or seen anything wrong with being called gay by losers in high school

07:01.680 --> 07:06.260
who had just as much growing up to do as I did. But when I actually was one of those

07:06.260 --> 07:11.800
people and knew it, all of a sudden it was a real judgment of who I actually was. To

07:11.800 --> 07:17.620
them I'd actually become lesser. Being told I was going to die of AIDS and that my feelings

07:17.620 --> 07:23.980
were unnatural and so on, and having to deal with being actually expected to try to convince

07:23.980 --> 07:29.140
people that I wasn't inferior to them, suddenly made me think about that Cthulhu film I'd

07:29.140 --> 07:35.900
seen a few years before. It was like it knew what I was going through. It knew how it felt

07:35.900 --> 07:41.940
to sit in a room you just can't leave and have a piece of your personhood interrogated.

07:41.940 --> 07:48.060
It knew how it felt to be seen as an outsider, and it knew how it felt to connect with someone

07:48.060 --> 07:53.700
who understands and accepts you. Somehow it knew me and how I'd felt before I'd ever

07:53.700 --> 07:58.940
had a chance to. Some of the scenes from this film just kept coming back up in my mind.

07:58.940 --> 08:04.460
It hadn't been what I'd thought I'd wanted, but what it was struck a chord with me anyway

08:04.460 --> 08:09.740
on a level I didn't know was there. It just took a while for me to hear the chiming.

08:09.740 --> 08:14.700
It turns out that some of the greatest horrors, biggest sources of sadness in our lives, don't

08:14.700 --> 08:19.580
come from scope or big questions, but from the tiniest things. If you've ever lost

08:19.580 --> 08:23.300
a loved one and had to be involved with the arrangements of their funeral, or if you've

08:23.300 --> 08:26.820
ever had to be around someone you'd made an effort to cut out of your life because

08:26.820 --> 08:31.380
of something abusive they'd done to you, or even something as simple as being reminded,

08:31.380 --> 08:35.380
gently, that you're in a place where everyone regards you with suspicion, that you're

08:35.380 --> 08:40.020
an outsider to them, you'll already know that the idea of a powerful cosmic monster

08:40.020 --> 08:44.860
out there somewhere beneath the sea can actually be the least of a person's problems.

08:44.860 --> 08:49.700
The film was, in retrospect, a meaningful and valuable work that paid respect to the

08:49.700 --> 08:55.240
source material's themes and emotions in ways I hadn't grasped as a cynical kid who

08:55.240 --> 09:00.860
thought he knew he was straight and thought he knew what made Lovecraft good, and I just

09:00.860 --> 09:04.340
wasn't ready to appreciate the value of that kind of story at the time.

