18:59.220 --> 19:02.500
I promise I'll review a game and make some jokes or something in the next one.

19:05.460 --> 19:06.020
Are they gone?

19:07.380 --> 19:08.420
Okay, they're gone.

19:08.420 --> 19:13.460
Right, so it's pop-culturally quite well known that Lovecraft was a bit xenophobic,

19:13.460 --> 19:16.660
and I do remember reading some pretty bad stuff,

19:16.660 --> 19:18.420
but it was a while ago that I read it,

19:18.420 --> 19:20.500
and I'm sure it can't be as bad as I remember.

19:20.500 --> 19:24.420
What the fuck is nautical looking supposed to mean, Howard?

19:24.420 --> 19:25.940
What does it even mean?

19:28.100 --> 19:32.420
...

19:32.420 --> 19:35.460
In his biography of H.P. Lovecraft, fittingly entitled

19:35.460 --> 19:38.020
Against the World Against Life,

19:38.020 --> 19:39.780
Michel Houellebecq writes,

19:39.780 --> 19:42.100
The character of Lovecraft fascinates us,

19:42.100 --> 19:45.860
partly because his system of values is entirely opposed to ours.

19:45.860 --> 19:48.340
Fundamentally racist, openly reactionary,

19:48.340 --> 19:52.180
he glorifies Puritan inhibition and quite evidently finds repellent

19:52.180 --> 19:54.420
any open display of eroticism.

19:54.420 --> 19:56.980
Resolutely anti-commercial, he despises money,

19:56.980 --> 20:00.500
considers democracy to be pure folly, progress an illusion.

20:00.500 --> 20:05.140
The word liberty, so dear to Americans, elicits from him only a gloomy sneer.

20:05.140 --> 20:08.740
All his life he maintained a typically aristocratic attitude of scorn

20:08.740 --> 20:12.180
for humanity in general together with an extreme solicitude

20:12.180 --> 20:14.420
toward individuals in person.

20:14.420 --> 20:17.380
Houellebecq kinda sucks, honestly,

20:17.380 --> 20:20.740
and idolizes some of Lovecraft's worst qualities in his biography,

20:20.740 --> 20:23.140
but this quote is helpful in illustrating the specifics

20:23.140 --> 20:25.300
of Lovecraft's worldview, so I'm gonna use it.

20:25.300 --> 20:28.260
A stopped clock is right twice a day, I suppose.

20:28.260 --> 20:31.140
Lovecraft seemingly hated society itself,

20:31.140 --> 20:33.540
but he had a deeper and specific dislike

20:33.540 --> 20:36.180
for Black and Jewish people along with immigrants.

20:36.180 --> 20:40.340
It's so prevalent in his writing that even citing multiple examples

20:40.340 --> 20:43.460
would kind of diminish how overwhelming and constant it is.

20:43.460 --> 20:48.020
I can't even bring myself to say the name of Lovecraft's cat

20:48.020 --> 20:49.860
because it's a racial slur.

20:49.860 --> 20:54.100
And despite this obviously completely full schedule of racism

20:54.100 --> 20:56.820
and general hatred for humanity itself,

20:56.820 --> 20:59.940
he also managed to find time to be a raging homophobe.

20:59.940 --> 21:02.660
He claimed not to have even known homosexuality existed

21:02.660 --> 21:04.340
until he was in his 30s,

21:04.340 --> 21:07.860
but then he goes on to immediately compare it to being a pederast.

21:07.860 --> 21:10.900
You know, growing up, I always would immediately try to find ways

21:10.900 --> 21:13.860
to write off or handwave away the racism.

21:13.860 --> 21:17.060
You know, I would say, well, it was a part of his time.

21:17.060 --> 21:19.940
I never really just sat down and gave myself the opportunity

21:19.940 --> 21:22.900
to just say, God, what a piece of shit.

21:24.100 --> 21:27.620
I mean, honestly, like, his work meant something to me

21:27.620 --> 21:29.780
in a really, like, profound way

21:29.780 --> 21:31.460
that no other work has ever really done,

21:32.340 --> 21:34.900
but I fucking think the guy's terrible.

21:34.900 --> 21:38.500
As a side note, Lovecraft's views apparently softened a little bit over time.

21:38.500 --> 21:40.340
In a letter he wrote a month before his death,

21:40.340 --> 21:42.340
he claimed he understood the blindness

21:42.340 --> 21:44.340
and defiant ignorance of reactionaries

21:44.340 --> 21:45.940
because he used to be one.

21:45.940 --> 21:49.140
"'I know how smugly ignorant I was,' he wrote.

21:49.140 --> 21:51.780
He supposedly became a socialist in the last year of his life

21:51.780 --> 21:53.060
and supported the New Deal,

21:53.060 --> 21:55.300
and he was married to a Jewish woman for a while,

21:55.300 --> 21:58.900
but it's debatable whether he really developed all that much,

21:58.980 --> 22:02.500
and the racism in his work is still unavoidably there.'"

22:02.500 --> 22:05.780
And this leads us to a very weird and difficult question.

22:06.820 --> 22:09.780
Why are there queer Lovecraft fans?

22:10.820 --> 22:12.020
Why do I exist?

22:12.980 --> 22:15.460
And why do so many people like me exist?

22:15.460 --> 22:18.340
Why is this space a place for a lot of queer

22:18.340 --> 22:20.420
and marginalized people in the first place?

22:21.140 --> 22:23.860
Why does his work resonate so well

22:24.580 --> 22:28.820
with people who the man himself would have hated even more

22:29.060 --> 22:30.500
than he hated everyone else?

22:31.300 --> 22:37.540
Now, I don't think I'm qualified to answer this question.

22:37.540 --> 22:40.580
I don't actually think anyone really is.

22:41.380 --> 22:43.140
There's probably a lot of different reasons,

22:44.020 --> 22:46.580
but from what I can gather,

22:47.300 --> 22:50.100
it seems like the answer lies in the specifics

22:50.100 --> 22:52.100
of how Lovecraft saw the world,

22:52.100 --> 22:55.460
in the place that his approach actually came from.

22:55.460 --> 22:57.300
"'When Lovecraft was three years old,

22:57.300 --> 22:58.500
his father had a breakdown

22:58.500 --> 23:00.100
and was committed to a mental hospital.

23:00.100 --> 23:01.700
He died there five years later.

23:01.700 --> 23:04.340
His mother also frequently suffered from similar problems

23:04.340 --> 23:06.740
and later died in the same hospital.

23:06.740 --> 23:10.100
Lovecraft suffered from periods of severe anxiety and depression.

23:10.100 --> 23:11.540
He had to drop out of high school

23:11.540 --> 23:14.340
and often isolated himself for long periods at a time.

23:14.340 --> 23:16.660
He saw himself as a temporary visitor

23:16.660 --> 23:18.660
to a strange and unwelcoming world.

23:18.660 --> 23:21.860
This is present even in one of Lovecraft's earliest stories,

23:21.860 --> 23:23.140
The Outsider.

23:23.140 --> 23:26.420
The narrator escapes from being trapped within a decaying castle,

23:26.420 --> 23:28.820
but his search for human contact is frustrated

23:28.820 --> 23:31.380
when the people he finds run away in horror.

23:31.380 --> 23:34.340
He turns and sees a detestable and ghoulish creature

23:34.340 --> 23:35.700
has entered the room.

23:35.700 --> 23:39.060
To his shock, he realizes he's looking into a mirror."

23:39.060 --> 23:41.860
All of his best works draw into close focus

23:41.860 --> 23:44.500
not some generic fear of outsiders,

23:45.220 --> 23:49.860
but the anxieties and fears that come with being an outsider,

23:50.420 --> 23:53.860
of being in a world that doesn't really understand you,

23:53.860 --> 23:58.180
and perhaps of not being fully able to understand yourself.

23:58.180 --> 24:00.340
So there is a fairly decent reason here

24:00.340 --> 24:02.340
why someone might be drawn to these works,

24:02.340 --> 24:04.820
even if the author was deeply problematic.

24:04.820 --> 24:07.300
And this appears to have been true to some degree

24:07.300 --> 24:08.900
at the time in a strange way.

24:08.900 --> 24:10.900
Lovecraft was pretty open about the problems

24:10.900 --> 24:12.420
he had with homosexuality.

24:12.420 --> 24:15.300
However, several of his closest friends were gay,

24:15.300 --> 24:18.260
including the poets Hart Crane and Samuel Loveman

24:18.260 --> 24:19.620
and Robert Hayward Barlow,

24:19.620 --> 24:21.940
who he worked closely with on numerous stories

24:21.940 --> 24:24.740
and who Lovecraft made the executor of his literary estate

24:24.740 --> 24:25.860
in the event of his death.

24:25.860 --> 24:27.380
It's partially due to Barlow

24:27.380 --> 24:28.900
that so much of Lovecraft's writing

24:28.900 --> 24:30.260
has been preserved over the years,

24:30.260 --> 24:32.900
given how he wasn't all that popular at the time.

24:32.900 --> 24:34.900
The deeply bigoted belief in a link

24:34.900 --> 24:36.820
between homosexuality and pedophilia

24:36.820 --> 24:38.740
is invoked, this time on purpose,

24:38.740 --> 24:39.940
in the film as well.

24:39.940 --> 24:42.100
There's a scene in Cthulhu where Russell is arrested

24:42.100 --> 24:44.660
on manufactured charges of being a pedophile.

24:44.660 --> 24:46.580
-"You're under arrest for murder." -"Oh, come on."

24:46.580 --> 24:48.260
-"Rape of a minor." -"Oh, wait, you can't--"

24:48.260 --> 24:50.020
-"Trespass--" -"The event is positioned

24:50.020 --> 24:51.700
as an extension of his mistreatment

24:51.700 --> 24:53.140
by the rest of the town.

24:53.140 --> 24:54.900
We're seeing the kind of alienation

24:54.900 --> 24:57.300
the original stories had to invent a foreign cult

24:57.300 --> 24:58.420
to get across,

24:58.420 --> 25:00.900
but translated into actual things

25:00.900 --> 25:02.580
people do experience."

25:02.580 --> 25:05.300
-"Oh, yeah, you like this? Faggot goes off to jail?"

25:05.300 --> 25:07.140
The easiness and convenience

25:07.140 --> 25:09.140
with which having a different sexual preference

25:09.140 --> 25:10.740
is equated with criminality

25:10.740 --> 25:13.940
is something that real people deal with even today.

25:13.940 --> 25:14.660
For some people,

25:14.660 --> 25:17.140
the intellectualized existential problems

25:17.140 --> 25:19.460
Lovecraft had originally written to explore

25:19.460 --> 25:20.900
cease to be theoretical

25:20.900 --> 25:23.140
and start to communicate familiar experiences

25:23.140 --> 25:25.220
the same way Edgar Allan Poe's writing can be

25:25.220 --> 25:26.820
to someone who's lost a loved one,

25:26.820 --> 25:28.500
or the way Halloween explores

25:28.500 --> 25:30.340
the suburban fear of one's neighbors,

25:30.340 --> 25:33.060
or Dracula puts words to a deeper understanding

25:33.060 --> 25:34.980
of the antagonism between different classes

25:34.980 --> 25:36.500
in our social hierarchy.

25:36.500 --> 25:38.580
For those who've been treated like this

25:38.580 --> 25:39.860
in the name of a religion

25:39.860 --> 25:42.100
or simply by their surrounding society

25:42.100 --> 25:44.340
because of its horrific expectations,

25:44.340 --> 25:47.220
have they not come the closest a person can

25:47.220 --> 25:48.500
in the real world

25:48.500 --> 25:50.980
to the central Lovecraftian experience?

25:50.980 --> 25:52.420
Have they not, in a sense,

25:52.420 --> 25:54.740
glimpsed the face of an uncaring universe?

25:59.700 --> 26:02.580
-"He was a guy that definitely did not get laid much,

26:03.140 --> 26:04.740
you know, and a guy that was

26:06.180 --> 26:07.780
an alien amongst us."

26:08.340 --> 26:10.100
Del Toro still hasn't gotten to make

26:10.100 --> 26:11.620
the Mountains of Madness adaptation

26:11.620 --> 26:13.700
he wanted to make and I wanted to see,

26:13.700 --> 26:14.820
but what's weird is,

26:14.820 --> 26:15.700
as I've grown older

26:15.700 --> 26:17.060
and become more interested in stories

26:17.060 --> 26:18.020
that are more compelling

26:18.020 --> 26:19.540
than Lovecraft's original works,

26:19.540 --> 26:21.540
it seems that Del Toro has as well.

26:21.540 --> 26:23.780
In a recent interview about The Shape of Water,

26:23.780 --> 26:24.420
he said,

26:34.420 --> 26:36.020
These are not concerns that I had

26:36.020 --> 26:37.780
when I was nine or seven.

26:37.780 --> 26:39.860
The Shape of Water doesn't have any elements

26:39.860 --> 26:40.820
that would be regarded

26:40.820 --> 26:42.340
as traditionally Lovecraftian

26:42.340 --> 26:43.860
by purists like Giles

26:43.860 --> 26:45.460
or the teenager I used to be,

26:45.540 --> 26:47.700
but its story gets at what I think

26:47.700 --> 26:49.140
makes Lovecraft actually work

26:49.140 --> 26:50.260
in the first place.

26:50.260 --> 26:52.340
Human stories about our alienation

26:52.340 --> 26:54.180
from each other and our lonelinesses,

26:54.180 --> 26:56.020
our victimization by forces

26:56.020 --> 26:56.980
beyond our control

26:56.980 --> 26:58.980
that see us as outside the norm,

26:58.980 --> 27:00.180
and how we can at least

27:00.180 --> 27:02.020
partially rectify this by

27:02.020 --> 27:03.380
learning to see the beauty

27:03.380 --> 27:05.300
in something previously seen as alien.

27:05.300 --> 27:06.180
In a sense,

27:06.180 --> 27:08.100
it's a story about the people of Innsmouth

27:08.100 --> 27:09.780
who happily chose to join

27:09.780 --> 27:10.820
with the Deep Ones,

27:10.820 --> 27:12.980
quite literally embracing otherness,

27:12.980 --> 27:14.580
raising children who literally

27:14.580 --> 27:16.500
learn to love to be different.

27:16.500 --> 27:18.180
Now, the film's perspectives

27:18.180 --> 27:19.620
and plot and texture

27:19.620 --> 27:20.900
make it not really invite

27:20.900 --> 27:22.580
much of a comparison with Lovecraft

27:22.580 --> 27:23.940
in a straightforward viewing,

27:24.580 --> 27:26.500
but maybe that's proof

27:26.500 --> 27:27.780
of how good it is.

27:27.780 --> 27:29.220
The Shape of Water has

27:29.220 --> 27:30.820
so successfully excavated

27:30.820 --> 27:32.020
all the garbage away

27:32.020 --> 27:33.540
from its spiritual predecessor

27:33.540 --> 27:34.900
that despite depicting something

27:34.900 --> 27:36.260
that directly happened

27:36.260 --> 27:37.460
in a story del Toro

27:37.460 --> 27:38.420
has definitely read,

27:38.980 --> 27:41.780
the comparison still feels strange,

27:41.780 --> 27:43.060
wrong almost.

27:43.060 --> 27:45.380
This film captures the beautiful,

27:45.380 --> 27:47.460
human, mesmerizing center

27:47.460 --> 27:48.820
of Lovecraft's writing.

27:48.820 --> 27:50.580
It's the kind of story he could,

27:51.220 --> 27:52.740
or perhaps should,

27:52.740 --> 27:54.340
have been writing all along.

27:54.340 --> 27:55.540
For me, there's something

27:55.540 --> 27:56.980
personally wonderful about

27:56.980 --> 27:58.260
finally really coming to

27:58.260 --> 27:59.380
an understanding of a film

27:59.380 --> 28:00.340
that touched me in ways

28:00.340 --> 28:01.220
I didn't realize

28:01.220 --> 28:02.340
and that never really

28:02.340 --> 28:03.780
got much recognition.

28:03.780 --> 28:05.380
Right as a film that understands

28:05.380 --> 28:06.820
this just as well gets released

28:06.820 --> 28:08.580
and actually gets major recognition

28:08.580 --> 28:09.700
and even wins an Oscar.

28:10.100 --> 28:11.540
I am an immigrant,

28:11.540 --> 28:13.220
unlike many, many of you,

28:13.220 --> 28:15.300
and in the last 25 years,

28:15.300 --> 28:16.980
I've been living in a country

28:16.980 --> 28:17.940
all of our own,

28:17.940 --> 28:18.740
because I think that

28:18.740 --> 28:20.500
the greatest thing our art does

28:20.500 --> 28:21.620
and our industry does

28:21.620 --> 28:23.380
is to erase the lines in the sand.

28:23.940 --> 28:25.780
We should continue doing that

28:25.780 --> 28:26.740
when the world tells us

28:26.740 --> 28:27.700
to make them deeper.

28:29.220 --> 28:31.380
While it's easy and correct

28:31.380 --> 28:33.140
to be dubious about the value

28:33.140 --> 28:34.340
of winning an Oscar,

28:34.340 --> 28:36.020
I do think the success of a film

28:36.020 --> 28:37.940
like this is a really hopeful sign

28:37.940 --> 28:39.300
for the future of how people

28:39.380 --> 28:41.140
see that which is alien to them.

28:41.140 --> 28:42.100
There's a philosopher

28:42.100 --> 28:43.300
named Julia Kristeva

28:43.300 --> 28:45.700
whose work was pretty formative for me.

28:45.700 --> 28:46.500
I discovered her

28:46.500 --> 28:47.700
through her being quoted

28:47.700 --> 28:48.980
in a series of critical essays

28:48.980 --> 28:49.940
on Lovecraft,

28:49.940 --> 28:51.300
one by Gina Whisker,

28:51.300 --> 28:53.460
entitled Spawn of the Pit.

28:53.460 --> 28:54.580
The quote went,

28:54.580 --> 28:56.580
By recognizing our uncanny strangeness,

28:56.580 --> 28:57.940
we shall neither suffer from it

28:57.940 --> 28:59.700
nor enjoy it from the outside.

28:59.700 --> 29:01.220
The foreigner is within me.

29:01.220 --> 29:03.140
Hence, we are all foreigners.

29:03.140 --> 29:04.260
If I am a foreigner,

29:04.260 --> 29:06.100
then there are no foreigners.

29:06.100 --> 29:07.700
Why be alien to each other

29:07.700 --> 29:10.020
when we are all alien to ourselves?

29:11.940 --> 29:13.460
So, what have we learned

29:13.460 --> 29:15.540
about how to adapt Lovecraft?

29:15.540 --> 29:17.300
Well, I think there's a point here

29:17.300 --> 29:18.900
about how we have to decide

29:18.900 --> 29:20.420
what really makes his work good

29:20.420 --> 29:21.380
in the first place,

29:21.380 --> 29:23.620
what the core truths in his work are

29:23.620 --> 29:24.660
that ought to survive

29:24.660 --> 29:26.100
into a future they inspire.

29:26.100 --> 29:27.860
An adaptation, to me at least,

29:27.860 --> 29:29.140
only needs fidelity

29:29.140 --> 29:30.260
to what really matters

29:30.260 --> 29:31.300
about the text,

29:31.300 --> 29:32.740
and neglecting to bring across

29:32.740 --> 29:33.940
other aspects like

29:33.940 --> 29:35.700
the finer points of its philosophy

29:35.700 --> 29:38.340
or its particular linguistic flourishes

29:38.340 --> 29:39.700
or certain characters

29:39.700 --> 29:42.260
or even its racism or homophobia

29:42.260 --> 29:44.260
isn't a failure to be fully faithful

29:44.260 --> 29:45.540
to the original work.

29:45.540 --> 29:46.500
It's demonstrating

29:46.500 --> 29:47.940
a successful understanding

29:47.940 --> 29:49.140
of why those stories

29:49.140 --> 29:50.340
were worth reading about

29:50.340 --> 29:51.220
in the first place

29:51.220 --> 29:52.660
in spite of those flaws.

29:52.660 --> 29:54.740
In focusing on a person's experiences

29:54.740 --> 29:56.340
and treatment for their sexuality

29:56.340 --> 29:57.380
or on a relationship

29:57.380 --> 29:58.820
with someone seen by others

29:58.820 --> 30:00.660
as an alien outsider,

30:00.660 --> 30:02.420
these works explore the originals

30:02.420 --> 30:04.340
and their feelings of otherness

30:04.420 --> 30:05.940
better than Lovecraft did.

30:05.940 --> 30:07.460
You don't have to go find a copy

30:07.460 --> 30:09.460
of this 10-year-old obscure film

30:09.460 --> 30:10.660
if you don't want to.

30:10.660 --> 30:12.180
It's not perfect by any means,

30:12.180 --> 30:13.380
and lots of the criticism

30:13.380 --> 30:14.900
the film's received is valid.

30:14.900 --> 30:16.180
Even the director's commentary

30:16.180 --> 30:16.980
opens by admitting

30:16.980 --> 30:18.660
they aren't fully happy with the film.

30:18.660 --> 30:21.540
There are 85 locations in this movie.

30:21.540 --> 30:22.580
Ridiculous.

30:22.580 --> 30:24.180
It's certainly nowhere near as good

30:24.180 --> 30:25.460
as the best film ever,

30:25.460 --> 30:27.220
Gremlins 2.

30:27.220 --> 30:28.740
But it meant something to me

30:28.740 --> 30:30.180
and was very important to me

30:30.180 --> 30:32.100
in a formative period of my life,

30:32.100 --> 30:33.620
and sometimes that's kind of

30:33.620 --> 30:35.140
more important than the writing

30:35.140 --> 30:36.420
or execution.

30:36.420 --> 30:38.020
As I look out into the internet

30:38.020 --> 30:39.860
and find many other queer fans

30:39.860 --> 30:41.140
of Lovecraft's work

30:41.140 --> 30:42.420
and writers in some form

30:42.420 --> 30:44.580
inspired by these feelings themselves,

30:44.580 --> 30:45.780
the wealth of literature

30:45.780 --> 30:47.620
exploring this side of his writing

30:47.620 --> 30:48.820
and films taking up

30:48.820 --> 30:50.580
radically humanizing perspectives

30:50.580 --> 30:52.180
even towards that which might

30:52.180 --> 30:54.580
literally be considered monstrous,

30:54.580 --> 30:55.620
I can't help but feel

30:55.620 --> 30:57.540
that there's a side of Lovecraft's work

30:57.540 --> 30:59.540
the man himself died

30:59.540 --> 31:02.340
unable to fully comprehend.

31:02.340 --> 31:05.220
And in a way, that's fitting, isn't it?

31:05.220 --> 31:06.900
But there's one other great story

31:06.900 --> 31:08.340
inspired at least partially

31:08.340 --> 31:09.620
by elements of Lovecraft,

31:09.620 --> 31:10.580
and I'm going to talk about it

31:10.580 --> 31:12.340
soon on my channel.

